#Text=Adam Folkard and Nick Norton ready for more men 's softball
#Text=Monday , March 19 , 2012

#Text=Hawker , Canberra — Coming off a national championship win for the Australian Capital Territory ( ACT ) men 's open team in mid-February , Australia men 's national softball team representatives Nick Norton and Adam Folkard are getting ready for more softball later this year , including the Australian club championships to be held in Brisbane in June .
#Text=Nick Norton at the ACT versus Japan women 's game Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=Adam Folkard at the ACT versus Japan women 's game Image : Laura Hale .
#Text=Folkard and Norton have both won the World Championships and have each won a total of ten national championships with the ACT side .

#Text=They are both named to the current men 's national team , which has roughly thirty players , and believe they are likely to survive the December cut down to eighteen players who will represent Australia at next year 's World Championship in Auckland , New Zealand .
#Text=The World Championship is one of the two most prestigious available to male softball players .
#Text=The other is the International Softball Congress , an event Folkard and Norton have both competed at .
#Text=As national team representatives , there are a lot of expectations for them .
#Text=In Australia , there is almost no financial support for the men 's game so they must cover most of their own costs , including travel to and from international competitions .
#Text=According to Folkard 's father , these costs can be prohibitive .
#Text=In one year , when Folkard was a representative on the men 's U18 , U23 and Open team , it cost A$ 15,000 for travel and other expenses just for Folkard .
#Text=When costs for bringing family members such as Folkard 's sisters to major international tournaments , the costs were even higher .
#Text=Folkard , his father and Norton all joked this cost his father an investment property to allow Folkard to continue to compete at the highest level .
#Text=Both Folkard and Norton currently work as tradesmen to support softball playing .
#Text=Beyond money , the national team requires players to be actively involved in wider softball community .
#Text=Players must represent a club at the club championships in Brisbane if they want to retain a spot in the squad .
#Text=Folkard plays for a Western Australian club and Norton plays for a Sydney based club , driving down from Canberra to play every Sunday during the season .

#Text=Folkard and Norton have both played softball at the highest level in the United States , where the men 's game is not yet fully professionalized but still presents more opportunities for players than are available at home .
#Text=For several years , Folkard has gone to the United States for three-month stints , playing for teams in Chicago , Pennsylvania , and New York .
#Text=One side he played was sponsored by Ernst and Young .
#Text=Folkard currently plays for a Canadian side and has been trying to convince Norton , whom he has grown up playing softball with , to join him like Norton has done one previous season .
#Text=According to Folkard , playing with a North American club has certain advantages .
#Text=The clubs pay for his travel to and from Australia , and pay for Championship rings .
#Text=When asked how North American clubs sign Australian players , he said they follow men 's softball in Australia and call up players to offer contracts .

#Text=Australian men 's players gain additional exposure to potential clubs when they compete , with some sides approaching them during the North American season and seeking to contract them for the following season .
#Text=Both men would love the opportunity to play softball in the Olympics , but believe such an opportunity is unlikely .
#Text=According to them , softball at the Olympics is a women 's game intrinsically linked to men 's baseball , and men 's softball is unlikely to ever be considered on the programme as a result .
#Text=Folkard and Norton both play for the same club in the ACT territory club competition .
#Text=Their team has secured a grand final berth for the match in ten days .
#Text=They are waiting to find out who they will play against based on a match this weekend .
#Text=Both have previously won this competition .
